  "prompt": "Why have so many professional wrestlers died young?",
  "response": "The premature deaths of many professional wrestlers can be attributed to several interrelated factors, including:\n\n1. **Physical Demands of the Profession**: Wrestling is a physically intense and demanding job. Wrestlers often endure rigorous training schedules, high-impact matches, and physically taxing travel routines, which can take a toll on their bodies.\n\n2. **Substance Abuse**: Some wrestlers have struggled with substance abuse, including the use of anabolic steroids, painkillers, and recreational drugs. The high-pressure environment, the need to maintain a certain physique, and the physical toll of the sport can contribute to this behavior.\n\n3. **Injuries and Chronic Health Problems**: Wrestlers are prone to injuries due to the nature of their performances. Chronic injuries can lead to long-term health issues that may contribute to early mortality.\n\n4. **Mental Health Issues**: The wrestling industry can be stressful, and some wrestlers have experienced mental health challenges, including depression and anxiety. In some cases, these issues may lead to substance abuse or other harmful behaviors.\n\n5. **Lack of Health Education and Support**: Historically, there has been a lack of adequate health education and support for wrestlers regarding the physical and mental health challenges they face. This can lead to poor lifestyle choices and overlooked health issues.\n\n6. **Workplace Environment**: The culture within some wrestling promotions has been known to prioritize performance over health, leading to wrestlers pushing themselves despite injuries or health concerns.\n\nThese factors combine to create a unique set of risks for professional wrestlers that can lead to premature deaths. Efforts have been made in recent years to address some of these issues, including increased awareness about mental health and substance abuse, as well as improved medical care and support for wrestlers.",
